ers have been added, and the final chapter charts a path to durable reform that would change New York's state government from its present-day status as a national disgrace to a model of transparent, more effective state politics and governance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aPolitical corruptionxNew York (State). 0aPolitical corruptionzNew York (State). 0aPower (Social sciences)xNew York (State). 0aPower (Social sciences)zNew York (State). 4aNew York/Regional : New York State Government. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Science. 4aPolitics and Law : Politics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / State.2bisacsh1 aPolner, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143846575340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438465753423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438465753/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles